India sent tanks and reinforcements to the frontier with Pakistan where soldiers from the two nations have been fighting.
The troops clashed in a remote border area in Kashmir.
A Pakistani official accused India of firing on civilians.
Despite tensions in the area, both countries downplayed the incidents as being localized and not serious.
Indian Prime Minister Singh said military directors from both countries were in touch.
India accuses Pakistan of supporting Moslem secessionists in Kashmir by providing arms and training, a charge Pakistan denies.
Since the Indian crackdown on the militants in January, at least 1,034 people have been killed. 
